passages.text: North America United States
In this edition of Cheat Sheets, we review key trends for the banking industry nearly two months into 3Q. We also include all key mgmt outlook comments on pages 25 and 26.

Traditional banking trends (such as NIM, loans, deposits, and credit) seem to be in line or a touch better than expected. Within capital markets, investment banking fees have improved throughout the quarter and there is much near- term optimism, which may bode well for September (the key month of the quarter). On the flipside, trading could be a little weaker than expected depending on how quickly activity picks up post the Labor Day holiday weekend.

Bank stocks are up \(44\%\) since the bottom in early April vs. a \(30\%\) rise in the S&P 500. Despite this move, we remain positive on the group as the fundamental backdrop for the group remains solid across the board.

Net interest income is poised to benefit from accelerating loan growth, continued fixed- asset repricing and positive deposit trends. Loan growth expectations remain low at most banks in our view so there's room for upside. The capital markets/IB backdrop continues to improve and should further accelerate as deal activity returns to historical norms. Trading revenues were robust in 1H (driven by EQ), but may be more resilient than anticipated, especially as IB activity picks up. Costs have been well managed. Most banks are expecting meaningful positive operating leverage in 2H, and consensus assumes even greater levels next year as revenue growth likely accelerates. Credit could become an earnings tailwind as CRE losses moderate and has been well reserved for. Capital levels are robust and the 2025 CCAR results were positive for the banks that participated. We acknowledge several key risks remain, namely deposit costs are still below historical levels relative to Fed funds (at \(55\%\) vs. a historical average of \(81\%\) ) and macro unknowns.

- Mega banks trade at 13.3x FY26 consensus estimates and large regionals trade at 10.9x vs. 20.9x for the S&P 500. This implies a relative multiple (vs. the S&P 500) of 64% for the mega banks (mostly in line with the 30-year historical average) and 52% for the large regionals (below the 30-year historical average).

- On P/B, mega banks trade at 2.1x vs. 1.8x for the large regionals.- Mega banks have an average div yield of 2.2% vs. 3.5% for the large regionals.- See pg. 7 where we track relative P/E multiples over the past 30 years.

Based on 2Q rate disclosures (as part of bank 10Q filings), net interest income would decline 2% on average among the banks we track in a 100bps down rate scenario (in line with last qtr). Currently the market is expecting 2 rate cuts by 12/31 and 3- 4 next year.

- The mega banks (ie BAC/C/JPM/WFC) remain more asset-sensitive than the large regionals. We estimate net II would decrease 5% in a falling rate scenario (in line with 1Q).- Large regionals are also slightly asset-sensitive. We estimate net II would decrease 2% (vs. -1% in 1Q) in a falling rates scenario.

Overnight SOFR rates (often a leading indicator for rate cuts/hikes) are down 8bps since 6/30. 30- day SOFR rates have remained stable, while 90- day SOFR rates are down 9bps. On an average basis (a better proxy for asset/liability repricing during the qtr), overnight, 30- and 90- day SOFR rates have all remained relatively stable. See page 17.

- Medium- and long-term Treasury yields have remained mostly stable on an average and spot basis throughout the quarter. 2-year and 5-year Treasury yields are each down 2-3bps vs. 6/30, while 10-year yields are up 5bps.- 30-year Agency MBS yields (a good proxy for bank securities books) are down 9bps vs. 6/30, and down 16bps on an average basis.- 30-year fixed mortgage rates are down 19bps vs. 6/30.

- According to the H8 data (as of August 13), total loans are up 0.7% since 6/30. This follows a solid 2Q, when total loans increased 1.7%. Growth in 3Q is being driven by CRE loans up 0.9%, C&I up 0.4%, credit card up 0.4%, other consumer up 0.9% (which is mostly indirect auto), and all others up nearly 1.6%. On a period-end basis vs. a year ago, total loans are up 4.3% vs. +3.6% in 2Q, +2.8% in 1Q, and +1.8% in 4Q. See page 16.- Total deposits are up slightly (+0.8%) vs. 6/30. This follows mostly stable levels in both 2Q and 1Q.- Total securities are up 2% on a spot basis vs. 6/30, a similar rise compared to the past two qtrs.- Cash is down slightly (-0.2%), which helps NIM and is relatively neutral to net II $ as banks likely rolled off some higher-cost funding and/or remixed cash into loans and securities.
Credit trends remain strong across bank portfolios. H8 data shows loan loss reserves are up slightly \((+0.5\%)\) since 6/30, and support loan growth vs. a slight decline in 2Q \((- 0.1\%)\) .

3Q IB fees are tracking up \(10 - 15\%\) both and yoy according to the Dealogic data. ECM and M&A advisory fees are leading the rebound, with DCM up modestly and syndicated loan fees down slightly (but showing improvement in recent weeks). We currently model 3Q IB fees to increase \(5\%\) yoy. See pages 18 and 22.

Completed M&A volumes are up \(46\%\) with announced volumes up \(24\%\) . These have both ground higher in recent weeks as deal sentiment improves. Total ECM volumes are up \(54\%\) yoy, with both IPOs and follow- on issuances up \(51\%\) . Total DCM volumes are down \(16\%\) , with IG down \(14\%\) and HY up \(38\%\) . Syndicated lending volumes are now up \(4\%\) QTD vs. down single digits the last several weeks. Both IG and HY volumes have improved throughout the quarter.

Trading trends have been mixed, with US equities volumes up sharply, while European equities/FICC trends have been more sluggish. Volatility continues to normalize. We currently model a \(6\%\) yoy rise in trading but believe trends are tracking slightly weaker than this.

In EQ, US cash trading volumes are up \(51\%\) yoy (through August 25), while European equities trading is down \(6\%\) . Derivative volumes we can track are up \(8\%\) yoy (as of 8/22). However, the VIX is down \(12\%\) so far in 3Q (after a \(25\%\) decline in 2Q). European volatility is also down \(5\%\) (measured by the VSTOXX index) after a \(20\%\) decline in 2Q. See page 19. Within FICC, fixed- income trading volumes we can track are down \(1\%\) yoy. FX volatility is also down \(11\%\) in 3Q (after a \(2\%\) increase in 2Q). US rates volatility is down \(14\%\) (following a \(11\%\) decline in 2Q). See page 19.

Macroeconomic fluctuations often account for most of the risks associated with exposures to instruments that promise to pay fixed or variable interest rates. For an investor who is long fixed- rate instruments (thus receiving these cash flows), increases in interest rates naturally lift the discount factors applied to the expected cash flows and thus cause a loss. The longer the maturity of a certain cash flow and the higher the move in the discount factor, the higher will be the loss. Upside surprises in inflation, fiscal funding needs, and FX depreciation rates are among the most common adverse macroeconomic shocks to receivers. But counterparty exposure, issuer creditworthiness, client segmentation, regulation (including changes in assets holding limits for different types of investors), changes in tax policies, currency convertibility (which may constrain currency conversion, repatriation of profits and/or liquidation of positions), and settlement issues related to local clearing houses are also important risk factors. The sensitivity of fixed- income instruments to macroeconomic shocks may be mitigated by indexing the contracted cash flows to inflation, to FX depreciation, or to specified interest rates - these are common in emerging markets. The index fixings may - by construction - lag or mis- measure the actual move in the underlying variables they are intended to track. The choice of the proper fixing (or metric) is particularly important in swaps markets, where floating coupon rates (i.e., coupons indexed to a typically short- dated interest rate reference index) are exchanged for fixed coupons. Funding in a currency that differs from the currency in which coupons are denominated carries FX risk.
